This might not be a bug, but i guess i'm looking for clarification here related to 'contex' kwargs while import vs export.

I was trying to do a non trivial thing with importing. I found a few references to contexts in the code and in your docs. I was trying to see how that would work to do what I was trying to do. I realized that this only really works for exporting. With the import process there seems like there are a few kwargs to  `convert` but it seems to terminate at `import_loop`, which is confusing to me as the pattern of export is what i would be looking for.

https://github.com/schematics/schematics/blob/development/schematics/transforms.py#L382

as the comment here says, import_loop, context is about default data not a context to pass the whole import chain.
https://github.com/schematics/schematics/blob/development/schematics/transforms.py#L63

After reading thru all of your code and found his PR, which i think is trying to solve the same thing i'm talking about.
https://github.com/schematics/schematics/pull/266

Finally I was able to hack a bit to get around this.
```python
from schematics.models import Model
from schematics.transforms import import_loop
from schematics.types.compound import ModelType, PolyModelType, MultiType

def context_convert(cls, instance_or_dict, context=None, partial=True, strict=False,
            mapping=None):
    def field_converter(field, value, mapping=None):
        try:
            return field.to_native(value, context=context, mapping=mapping)
        except Exception:
            return field.to_native(value, context=context)
    data = import_loop(cls, instance_or_dict, field_converter,
                       partial=partial, strict=strict, mapping=mapping)
    return data

class ContextModel(Model):
  def __init__(self, raw_data=None, context=None, deserialize_mapping=None, strict=True):
      if raw_data is None:
          raw_data = {}
      self._initial = raw_data
      self._data = self.convert(raw_data, context=context, strict=strict, mapping=deserialize_mapping)  

  def convert(self, raw_data, **kw):  
      """
      Converts the raw data into richer Python constructs according to the
      fields on the model
      :param raw_data:
          The data to be converted
      """
      return context_convert(self.__class__, raw_data, **kw)   
```

The issue was raised in [some comments](./410#issuecomment-361974051) in #410 and #409 that the rules for broadcasting outputs are inconsistent among the single diode methods

* `singlediode` will only broadcast the output if `photocurrent` is an sequence, array or series
    - float -> OrderedDict of float
    - array or sequence -> OrderedDict of array or sequence
    - Series -> DataFrame
* `i_from_v` will broadcast the smallest size of either `voltage`, `photocurrent`, or `resistance_shunt`
* `v_from_i` will broadcast the smallest size of either `current`, `photocurrent`, or `resistance_shunt`

In those same comments @cwhanse proposed:
> to expand singletons when any parameter input is a vector, and to fail (gracefully) if two parameters are vectors of unequal length

I agree with this idea, and both `i_from_v` and `v_from_i` already have some boilerplate code to address this (note this snippet is lifted from `v_from_i`, with variable names suited for that function, change the
arguments to other methods like singlediode or mpp):

        # find the right size and shape for returns
        args = (current, photocurrent, resistance_shunt)  <-- list the args allowed to broadcast here
        size = 0
        shape = None
        for n, arg in enumerate(args):
            try:
                this_shape = arg.shape
            except AttributeError:
                this_shape = None
                try:
                    this_size = len(arg)
                except TypeError:
                    this_size = 0
            else:
                this_size = sum(this_shape)
                if shape is None:
                    shape = this_shape
            if this_size > size and size <= 1:
                size = this_size
                if this_shape is not None:
                    shape = this_shape
                    # there is no check for consistent shape
            else:
                # raise an exception here if you want
                pass  # do nothing to choose the smallest size

Now knowing the `size` and/or the `shape` one can let [`numpy.vectorize`](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/generated/numpy.vectorize.html) cast the output as proposed:

        if size <= 1:
            V = v_from_i_fun(current, photocurrent, saturation_current,
                             resistance_series, resistance_shunt, nNsVth)
            if shape is not None:
                V = np.tile(V, shape)  <-- hacky way to make either array(V), array([V]), array([[V]]), ...
        else:
            vecfun = np.vectorize(v_from_i_fun)  <-- let numpy do the broadcasting for us!
            V = vecfun(current, photocurrent, saturation_current,
                       resistance_series, resistance_shunt, nNsVth)
        if np.isnan(V).any() and size <= 1:
            V = np.repeat(V, size)
            if shape is not None:
                V = V.reshape(shape)

On a related note: @cwhanse I realize now I misread [your comment](./410#issuecomment-362112394) and made `i_from_v` and `v_from_i` fail _silently_ instead of _gracefully. This might cause some confusion, in the short term, but maybe we can address it in this issue here?

@wholmgren is there a `PVLibException` class? What exception would you expect here, maybe `ValueError('All arguments must be either scalar or the same size.')`?

